{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0b59c142-1c27-4d2b-b1fd-64a909373e31","content":"It looks like the project doesn't exist yet. No worries — here's exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP stdio server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- These make it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required; tools must be executables.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all the configuration needed — no special MCP packaging is required since stdio tools are just executables.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"03a1ba20-3859-4919-853a-3aed668062d6","outputTokens":495,"requestId":"6416:19B7FC:269D172:2B7641D:69EB4E48"},"id":"2b9b7bc6-e5bc-4942-b3b0-6b780c6b4218","timestamp":"2026-04-24T11:04:49.998Z","parentId":"8b6e52cd-2edb-458f-a63c-a4b90548e59e"}
